notes: Song of the Sea - Late 13th century BCE, one of the earliest Hebrew poems. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Balaam's oracle - 11th-10th century BCE. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Song of Moses - 12th-8th century BCE (not including editorializing layer of 32:44-55). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Song of Deborah - Late 12th-late 11th century BCE (alternative datings to monarchic period have been advanced). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Psalm 29 specifically dated to 12th-10th century BCE, one of the earliest psalms. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Post-exilic work combining Priestly and non-Priestly material. Final form reached in Persian period. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Anthology drawn from nearly all periods of Israel's history, reaching final form in Persian period. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Entirely Priestly material dating from the exilic/post-exilic period. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Final form reached in Persian period, combining material from various periods. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Priestly Blessing - Late 7th-early 6th century BCE. From oldest surviving Biblical text, the Ketef Hinnom scrolls. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Core religious laws from reign of Josiah (late 7th century BCE). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Expanded with addition of chapters 1-4 and 29-30 to serve as introduction to Deuteronomistic history. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Revised with expansions to chapters 19-25 and addition of chapters 27 and 31-34 to serve as conclusion to the Torah. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Part of Deuteronomistic history, first edition during Josiah's reign (late 7th century BCE). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Completion of Deuteronomistic history during Babylonian exile (6th century BCE). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)

Completion of Deuteronomistic history during Babylonian exile. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Proto-Isaiah/First Isaiah: Original 8th century BCE Isaiah material (late 8th-early 7th century). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Deutero-Isaiah/Second Isaiah: Anonymous prophet living in Babylon during exile, active around mid-6th century BCE. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Trito-Isaiah/Third Isaiah: Anonymous author(s) in Jerusalem immediately after the exile. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Jeremiah active in last decade of 7th century and first decades of 6th century BCE. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Later Masoretic Hebrew version finalized in Persian period. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Ezekiel active in Babylon 592-571 BCE. Book reflects historic Ezekiel with significant additions by later followers. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Second half of 8th century BCE (late 8th-early 7th). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Expansion and reshaping during exilic period (6th century BCE). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)

Persian or Hellenistic period, no later than 2nd century BCE. Regarded as fictional by scholars. [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Original 8th century material, approximately 750-700 BCE (late 8th-early 7th century). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
Oracle concerning Nineveh, written around the Assyrian city's destruction in 612 BCE (7th century). [Source](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dating_the_Bible)
